1122917399932604416.text:
It's never been observed to decay on its own, but scientists have made it decay by hitting it with x-rays to.
It's literally 'moving too fast to die'.
The same angular momentum conservation requirement also slows the beta decay that the ground state uses.

1122916393354235909.text:
That excited state also has extra orbital angular momentum which has to be lost with the gamma ray photon, this slows decay down. For every unit of angular momentum in a transition, gamma decay gets about 100,000 times slower.
Tantalum 180m needs to get rid of 8 units of AM.

1122915882693533697.text:
Tantalum 180m is real freak though. 
Regular Tantalum 180 wants to undergo beta decay with a half life of hours.
The 'm' indicated a 'metastable' excited state, it's got extra energy that normally would escape via gamma rays.

1122914953235763200.text: For some reference - Tellurium 128 is probably the longest lived isotope predicted to decay via double beta decay to Xe 128 with a 2.2E24 year half life. Which is 100x the half life of Xe 124 that recently made the news.
